{"id":"1509.00348","submitter":"Lucas Clemente","authors":"Lucas Clemente, Johannes Kofler","title":"No Fine theorem for macrorealism: Limitations of the Leggett-Garg\n  inequality","comments":"6 pages, published version, comments welcome","journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Lett. 116, 150401 (2016)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevLett.116.150401","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Tests of local realism and macrorealism have historically been discussed in\nvery similar terms: Leggett-Garg inequalities follow Bell inequalities as\nnecessary conditions for classical behavior. Here, we compare the probability\npolytopes spanned by all measurable probability distributions for both\nscenarios and show that their structure differs strongly between spatially and\ntemporally separated measurements. We arrive at the conclusion that, in\ncontrast to tests of local realism where Bell inequalities form a necessary and\nsufficient set of conditions, no set of inequalities can ever be necessary and\nsufficient for a macrorealistic description. Fine's famous proof that Bell\ninequalities are necessary and sufficient for the existence of a local\nrealistic model, therefore cannot be transferred to macrorealism. A recently\nproposed condition, no-signaling in time, fulfills this criterion, and we show\nwhy it is better suited for future experimental tests and theoretical studies\nof macrorealism. Our work thereby identifies a major difference between the\nmathematical structures of local realism and macrorealism.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 1 Sep 2015 15:19:20 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Sat, 24 Oct 2015 16:11:49 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 21 Apr 2016 18:36:28 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-04-22"}
